{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521407"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:34:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:34:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13624"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13624"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.09,0.78,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97101"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6232"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79704"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33304"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97101"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of dysuria, increased urinary frequency, and urgency. He denies having haematuria or nocturia. He reports that he has had similar episodes in the past which were managed with a course of cephalexin. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. He is unsure of his regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely contributing to his presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Semaglutide","Metformin","Spironolactone","Dapagliflozin","Gliclazide"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of a urinary tract infection (UTI), including dysuria, frequency, and urgency. Given his history of recurrent UTIs and type 2 diabetes, it\u0027s important to consider whether any of his medications could be contributing to this problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDapagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E, a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitor, is the most likely medication contributing to his recurrent UTIs. SGLT2 inhibitors work by reducing glucose reabsorption in the proximal renal tubules, leading to increased urinary glucose excretion. This mechanism can increase the risk of UTIs, as the elevated urinary glucose provides a favourable environment for bacterial growth. While not mentioned in the patient\u0027s current medication list, it\u0027s possible that he has been prescribed this medication given his history of type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESemaglutide\u003C/strong\u003E is a glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) receptor agonist used in the treatment of type 2 diabetes. Its main side effects include nausea, vomiting, and diarrhoea. It does not increase the risk of UTIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E is a biguanide that reduces hepatic glucose production and improves insulin sensitivity. While it can cause gastrointestinal side effects, it does not increase the risk of UTIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E is a potassium-sparing diuretic often used in the treatment of hypertension. Its main side effects include hyperkalaemia and gynaecomastia. It does not increase the risk of UTIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGliclazide\u003C/strong\u003E is a sulfonylurea that stimulates insulin release from pancreatic beta cells. Its main side effects are hypoglycaemia and weight gain. It does not increase the risk of UTIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing this patient, it would be important to confirm the diagnosis of UTI with appropriate tests, treat the current infection, and review his diabetes management. If he is indeed taking an SGLT2 inhibitor like dapagliflozin, the risks and benefits of continuing this medication should be carefully considered, especially in light of his recurrent UTIs. Alternative diabetes medications or additional preventive strategies for UTIs might need to be explored.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SGLT2 inhibitors increase the risk of recurrent urinary tract infections.","Symptoms of urinary tract infection include dysuria, frequency, and urgency."],"references":["Petersons CJ. Second steps in managing type 2 diabetes. Australian Prescriber. 2018;41(5):141\u20134. doi:10.18773/austprescr.2018.043"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79704"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13624"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79704"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T20:38:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T20:40:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6232"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97101"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"cre